**Abstract:**
Notes dated January 27, 1994, engaging with Eugene Garver's critique of speech act theory, particularly Searle's inadequate treatment of declaratives. The document examines the distinction between constatives and performatives, arguing that Searle's simple word-world dichotomy cannot capture the "ambiguous direction of fit" inherent in rhetoric and serious discourse. It connects this to the author's broader critique of representational theories of language and the primacy accorded to propositional speech acts.

**AI Recommendation:** Important engagement with speech act theory; develops critique of language philosophy relevant to broader project.

